{ Welcome and thank you for purchasing the third and final part of my Lifetime Repertoires series on 1. e4.

We’re going to take a look at the entire Sicilian Defense, so after 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 everything is covered, and if you have this course you will be ready to play against all of Black's attempts.

I will share with you many different ideas. I don’t have a one-fits-all approach. I think chess is a more complicated game, and if you want to play ambitiously, you can’t just do the same thing against everything. In a game, you have to constantly adapt to your opponent’s play, sometimes playing positional, sometimes playing tactical, sometimes preventing your opponent's threats and sometimes creating your own.

I have tried to stay true to my philosophy, as I think I did in the first two parts of this series, which is to provide variations and systems suitable for both very strong players and amateurs. } 1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} c5 
2. Nf3 d6 { There are a lot of sidelines on move 2 which are covered in chapter 18 [/course/159903/13], Black's Sidelines: 2...e6 and chapter 19 [/course/159903/14] Black's Sidelines Without ...e6. } ( { • Against the O'Kelly Variation, } 2...a6 { I go for the Maroczy Bind. } 3.c4 { We will see this setup against different Sicilians, for example in the Dragon without ...Nf6, @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 g6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nc6 5.c4 or in the Kan: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 a6 5.c4 . } ) ( { • } 2...Nf6 { Another popular sideline, the Nimzo-Rubinstein, is big enough to have its own chapter [/course/159903/11]. } ) ( { • } 2...e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nc6 5.Nc3 Qc7 { The 5... Qc7 Taimanov has two dedicated chapters; } 6.Be3 a6 7.Qf3 { is my recommendation in the mainline. } ) ( { • } 2...e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nc6 5.Nc3 a6 { The 5... a6 Taimanov, where } 6.Nxc6 { is very attractive, as after } 6...bxc6 { the a6-pawn turned out to be just a waste of tempo. I recommend a simple setup with } 7.Bd3 d5 8.O-O Nf6 9.Qf3 { . } ) ( { • } 2...e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 { The Four Knights Sicilian. } 6.Ndb5 { Here after } 6...d6 7.Bf4 e5 8.Bg5 { we transpose to the Sveshnikov. To give you a little taste of what's coming in the Sveshnikov, after } 8...a6 9.Na3 b5 { the rare } 10.Nb1 { is the new little twist. } ) ( { • } 2...Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 e5 5.Nb5 d6 6.N1c3 { The Kalashnikov. Here Black can transpose to the Sveshnikov, but can also try ...a6-b5, ...Be6 or ... Be7. All these lines are covered in chapter 8 [/course/159903/8]. } ) ( { • } 2...d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 g6 { The Dragon, one of my own openings for Black, where I recommend the main Yugoslav Attack with Be3, f3 and Qd2. But, to make one point clear, I have not been able to refute my own course :) I recommend a very promising line, in which Black, with very precise play, can equalize, but in practical games, even very strong grandmasters have failed to do so. } ) ( { • } 2...d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e6 { The Scheveningen Sicilian is considered very dubious nowadays, because of the Keres Attack } 6.g4 { , wich is of course explained in detail in chapter 5 [/course/159903/7]. } ) ( { • } 2...d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 { Another big part of the course is the Classical Sicilian, against which I recommend } 6.Bg5 { , the Rauzer. } ) 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 a6 { The Najdorf is of course a very big part of this course. } 
6. h3 { I'm very happy with my recommendation. This is a very big line, Black has many options, and that is why there is an overview of Najdorf in the course, but I will give you a small preview of the ...e5 mainline. } e5 
7. Nf3 { The knight is surprisingly well placed here. The advance on g4-g5 is often aimed at, and the knight will be of great use in supporting it, especially when Black plays ...h6. } *

