1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 a6 
6. h3 e5 
7. Nf3 Be7 { The most popular move and also definitely the most natural one. Black intends to finish the development of the kingside and keeps everything else flexible for now. } 
8. g4! {[%cal Gg4g5]} { I wasn't joking when I drew that g2-g4 arrow after 6. h3. Our intentions are to challenge Black on the kingside here and threaten the kingside expansion. } h6 { The most common reply and the one approved by the engines. Black chooses not to allow us to push the g4 pawn further without consequences, but thanks to our knight on f3, we have g5 hxg5 Nxg5 idea at our disposal. } 
9. Rg1 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gf3g5][%csl Gg1]} ( { Preparing g5 hxg5 Nxg5 operation. The direct } 9.g5 { is not a terrible attempt either, but allows the extra } 9...hxg5 10.Nxg5 Bg4! { option, which is better avoided. The rook anyway belongs on the g-file so the text move is the most challenging. Instead, @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p2bpp1/p2p1n1p/4p3/4P1P1/2N2N1P/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@ 9.Be3 Be6 could transpose back into another trendy variation - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Be3 e5 7.Nf3 Be7 8.h3 Be6 9.g4 h6 which has been covered in my Najdorf course and is less poisonous than this one, where we delay Be3 for now. } ) Nc6 { This move played against me by Wei Yi is somewhat unusual in the Najdorf, but is quite decent here. } 
10. g5 hxg5 
11. Nxg5 Be6 { Wei Yi tried to transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Be3 e5 7.Nf3 Be7 8.h3 Be6 9.g4 h6 10.g5 hxg5 11.Nxg5 Nc6 variation, which works for Black, but here White gets extra options, as we can keep delaying Be3. Alternatively Black can play @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1p2bpp1/p1np1n2/4p1N1/4P3/2N4P/PPP2P2/R1BQKBR1 b Qkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@ 11...Nd4 , but after 12.Bc4 they have to know what they are doing. } 
12. Nxe6 fxe6 
13. Rxg7! Qb6 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gd6d5]} { Black is trying for counterplay, but here I prepared a nasty idea. } 
14. a4! {[%cal Ga4a5][%csl Rb6]} { The queen is suddenly not feeling too comfortable. } Qb4?! 
15. Bd2! -- ( { The e4 pawn is now poisoned. After } 15...Nxe4 { the variation is actually very calculate-able: } 16.Rxe7+! Nxe7 17.Qg4 { Black is losing the knight on the pin. You can find the complete line analysis here. [/variation/24595451] } )
