9. Rg1 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gf3g5][%csl Gg1]} ( { Preparing g5 hxg5 Nxg5 operation. The direct } 9.g5 { is not a terrible attempt either, but allows the extra } 9...hxg5 10.Nxg5 Bg4! { option, which is better avoided. The rook anyway belongs on the g-file so the text move is the most challenging. Instead, @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p2bpp1/p2p1n1p/4p3/4P1P1/2N2N1P/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@ 9.Be3 Be6 could transpose back into another trendy variation - @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Be3 e5 7.Nf3 Be7 8.h3 Be6 9.g4 h6 which has been covered in my Najdorf course and is less poisonous than this one, where we delay Be3 for now. } ) b5 { The most often played move, though at this point there aren't all too many games left and multiple options seem just as likely. Black starts queenside expansion of their own. } 
10. g5 {[%mdl 32768]} { Following the plan. } hxg5 
11. Nxg5 {[%cal Gc1e3,Ya2a4,Yf1c4][%csl Gg5]} { The knight sits beautifully here, undisturbed and eyeing the f7 pawn. We want to finish the development with Be3, Qd2 and O-O-O, but we do have to keep in mind the @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/4bpp1/p2p1n2/1p2p1N1/4P3/2N4P/PPP2P2/R1BQKBR1 w Qkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@ 12.a4 b4 13.Bc4! sequence which can be very nasty under the right circumstances. } Bb7 {[%csl Gd5]} ( { The obvious move, but Black does have options here. I will cover the ones that have been played before. The text move is best, developing a piece, but also guarding the d5 square, preventing a4 b4 Nd5! operation. } 11...Nbd7 { or } ) ( 11...Nc6 { are also possible, but that allows } 12.a4 b4 13.Nd5 { , when White can recapture on d5 with the queen. } ) 
12. Be3 ( { Black rightly didn't fear the } 12.a4 b4 13.Bc4 { just yet, because that apparently doesn't work, since after } 13...bxc3 14.Bxf7+ Kf8 15.Ne6+ Kxf7 16.Nxd8+ Rxd8 { Black collects more than enough material for the queen. Instead, we should continue our development first. Black, once again has a choice here. Although remembering various options that Black has is a problem for us, giving opponents a lot of choices is a good thing on many levels. First, it will cost them a lot of time to choose between them and secondly when they have to make choices, they are likely to regret their decisions when faced with problems later. } ) Nbd7 { This is what we are hoping for, which is also the most natural move, completing the development, seemingly harmoniously. } 
13. a4! b4 { Black is better off giving up a pawn at this point, but of course this is the most natural and also the move that has been played so far. } 
14. Bc4 { Black is in a bad shape here as none of the three options are attractive here at this point. } bxc3 { Objectively this is the best move apparently, but in reality I don't expect Black to make it out alive here, even though the computer upon further thought thinks this may not be completely losing. } 
15. Bxf7+ Kf8 
16. Bg6! {[%cal Gg5e6][%csl Gg6]} ( { We don't want to grab the queen for three pieces with } 16.Ne6+? { and apparently } ) ( 16.Ba2 { is less strong, since after } 16...cxb2 17.Ne6+ Ke8 { Black gets a decent version of things and we don't have more than a perpetual. For the purposes of the Quickstarter Guide, the line ends here. The full analysis can be found in Chapter 1 [/variation/25761253/#/16/w]. } ) *

