1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 a6 
6. h3 e5 
7. Nf3 Be7 { The most popular move and also definitely the most natural one. Black intends to finish the development of the kingside and keeps everything else flexible for now. } ( 7...Be6 { is usually not done, when White can go after it with a knight. } 8.Ng5! Be7 9.Nxe6 fxe6 10.Bc4 Qd7 11.a3 { Securing the bishop, with a more pleasant position. } ) 
8. g4! {[%cal Gg4g5]} { I wasn't joking when I drew that g2-g4 arrow after 6. h3. Our intentions are to challenge Black on the kingside here and threaten the kingside expansion. } Be6 { The second most often played move so far and definitely a sensible one. Black allows g5, but continues the standard Najdorf development scheme. } ( 8...O-O { This move is very provocative, but actually not bad. We can simply transpose to a line covered in 8... Be6 to save ourselves the extra work. } 9.g5 Nh5 10.h4 { I tried to be fancy and use the fact that Black delayed Be6 with 10. Bc4, but the best is to keep it simple and just follow the usual plan. } 10...Be6 11.Be3 { It is interesting to explore the complications after 11.Nh2!? Nf4 , but the text move will transpose us to a big tabia that we get after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p2bppp/p2p1n2/4p3/4P1P1/2N2N1P/PPP2P2/R1BQKB1R b KQkq g3 0 8@@EndFEN@@ 8...Be6 9.g5 Nh5 10.h4 Nd7 11.Be3 O-O . Black should go @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/1p2bppp/p2pb3/4p1Pn/4P2P/2N1BN2/PPP2P2/R2QKB1R b KQ - 2 11@@EndFEN@@ 11...Nd7 here, transposing. }) 
9. g5 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Also interesting is } 9.Ng5!? { . } ) Nfd7 {[%cal Gd7b6]} { Sending the knight towards b6 is very standard. Now White has two ways to play and the challenge for Black is to reply to each of them correctly. } 
10. Be3 ( { I like this move, aimed against the natural b5 push, after which Black would want to harmoniously position their knights with Nb6 and N8d7. White could instead start with } 10.h4 { , but then } 10...b5! { followed by Nb6 would give Black decent counterplay, even though there too, White can ask some questions. } ) Nb6 { This is the way to go for Black. There is no time for b5 here and Black needs to complete the queenside development in order to get some counterplay. } 
11. h4 ( { The most natural is to push the kingside pawns first. } 11.Qd2 { would likely lead to the same thing, since h4-h5 will come on the next moves anyway. Alternatively } ) ( 11.a4!? { is challenging as well with idea } 11...N8d7 12.a5 Nc4 13.Bxc4 Bxc4 14.Nd5 { when Black has to react well to get adequate counterplay. } ) N8d7 
12. h5 Rc8 
13. Qd2 { This position has occurred in the game Petkov-Sethuraman 2021. Despite being a great theoretician, I assume Sethuraman was already on his own in this somewhat unusual Najdorf position and he went mildly astray with the most natural of the moves. } Nc4 { Tempting, but already very inaccurate. } 
14. Bxc4 Rxc4 { Here White missed a great chance in the game Petkov-Sethuraman [/variation/25630272]. } 
15. Nh4! {[%cal Gh4f5][%csl Gh4]} { A thematic idea in this variation. The f3 knight proves itself highly useful. Now Black has a choice of either letting Nf5 happen, which is obviously no fun, or going for g6, which makes castling short virtually impossible, due to White being able to open the h-file on demand. } g6 
16. b3 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gc1b2]} { A commital move, but the king on b2 is going to be very safe in fact. } Rc8 
17. O-O-O Qa5 
18. Kb2 {[%csl Gb2,Re8]} { Our king is nicely tucked in while the same cannot be said about its black counterpart. } *

