1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 a6 
6. h3 e6 
7. g4 {[%mdl 32768]} Be7 
8. g5 ( { We can probably start with } 8.Bg2 { as well and transpose later, but it is more natural to first kick the knight away. } ) Nfd7 
9. Bg2!? Nc6 ( { This is a reasonably fresh trend, aimed against b5 setups. Going for the old main line with h4/Be3/a3/Qd2 in some order is obviously possible, but I decided to go for a more modern approach, trying to take our opponent out of their standard setup. I should mention also that } 9...Bxg5? { is wrong because of a cute thematic tactic - } 10.Nxe6! fxe6 11.Qh5+ { with the double attack, regaining the piece. } ) { The most common move and a very decent one as well, now that we have committed the bishop to g2. } 
10. h4 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2][%csl Gc1,Gg5,Gh4]} { Pushing the kingside pawns and keeping the c1 bishop flexible for now. We might have other plans for it, than the obvious e3 square... } Qc7 {[%csl Rc8]} { This is logical as well, intending b5, though Black isn't going to get a great version of these positions here, with the queen on c6, instead of the bishop. } 
11. f4 b5 
12. Nxc6! {[%cal Rc7c6][%csl Rc7]} { Black's bishop belongs on c6 in these positions, not the queen. } Qxc6 
13. Be3 ( { Direct } 13.Qd4!? { is also good. } ) Bb7 
14. Qd4! {[%cal Ge1c1,Gh4h5]} { And White had a great version of these typical Scheveningen races in Bok-Kozganbay [/variation/25655097], 2012. White's play comes much faster, with h5-h6 being the idea, after Black castles short. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's 1. e4  -  Part 3"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Najdorf: 6.h3 e6 #2"]
[Date "2023.03.29"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/25655159"]
[ECO "B90"]

1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 a6 
6. h3 e6 
7. g4 d5 
8. exd5 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { The main move and the one I would like to recommend, even though there are interesting alternatives for White, such as } 8.Nde2!? { . } ) Nxd5 
9. Nde2 {[%csl Rd5]} { The way to play for White, challenging the knight on d5. Now Black has a bunch of options, in all of which equality is in sight, but nothing seems quite comfortable for Black either. Another important thing to keep in mind, is that the positions are often one-sided, which is something let's say the Berlin or the Petroff players would accept, but not what the Najdorf boys are in here for. } Bb4 { This used to be the main move and is by far the most played one according to my database. Black develops the kingside first. } 
10. Bg2 ( { There is a clever option of } 10.a3!? { as well, which I believe I wasn't aware of, back in the day when this line was hype. } ) O-O 
11. O-O { Now Black has two options. At some point taking with the bishop was supposed to equalize, but then White discovered a pawn sacrifice that keeps the fire burning. Taking with the knight instead, always looked slightly worse for Black. The main issue Black is facing in these positions is the bishop on c8, which looks very miserable compared to our fianchettoed monster on g2. } Nxc3 
12. Nxc3 Qc7 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7c6]} { Black keeps the queens on the board, in hope to develop the c8 bishop. } 
13. Qd4 ( { Alternatively, } 13.Qf3 { is also quite challenging, but I like the fancy queen maneuver to c4. } ) Nc6 
14. Qc4! ( { Keeping the tension, since } 14.Bxc6 Bxc3 { is leading to an endgame that seems just too drawish. } ) Bd6 
15. Ne4!? -- ( { Clever to start with Ne4, not allowing Black the b5 push, which can now be met with } 15...b5 16.Qxc6 Qxc6 17.Nf6+ { tactic. For the purposes of the Quickstarter Guide, the line ends here. The full analysis can be found in Chapter 3. [/variation/24601218] } )
*

