6. h3 g6 
7. Be3 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1,Gf2f3][%csl Ra6,Rh3]} { I propose to go for the Yugoslav Attack style setup and try to save on the move g4. The move h3 will rarely be useful, but a6 is also not a game changer. } Bg7 
8. Qd2 O-O ( { The most natural and common move, but already a mistake. } 8...Nbd7 { is rare, but extremely clever. Black is playing in the best traditions of the Dragodorf, trying to stay flexible. You can study it starting from here [/variation/24616808]. @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/1p2ppbp/p2p1np1/8/3NP3/2N1B2P/PPPQ1PP1/R3KB1R b KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@ 8...Nc6 is the alternative, and you can find it here [/variation/24616810]. } ) 
9. O-O-O b5 ( { Let's see how Swedish Nr.1 my good friend and a great theoretician Nils Grandelius managed to get lost in two more moves here. For } 9...Nc6 { see 8... Nc6 line [/variation/24616810]. } ) 
10. f3 Bb7 ( { Better is } 10...b4 { , but there too after } 11.Nce2 { ( } { 11.Nd5 also possible), our play with h4-h5 is faster. } ) 
11. h4 Nbd7 
12. h5! {[%cal Gh1h7][%csl Gc1,Rg8]} { White is just winning here already. Stojanovic-Grandelius [/variation/25631854], 1-0 2013. } *

