1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 e6 { The Scheveningen Sicilian was a very respectable opening for a very long time. It is a sound setup with a sound pawn structure, but in this particular version of it, the pure Scheveningen, so-called, White gets an opportunity to go for the direct 6. g4! called the Keres Attack.

For the Scheveningen fans, I recommend playing the Najdorf and only after White makes a developing move on move 6, such as 6. h3 (or 6. Be3, 6. Be2, 6. f3 etc) to only then play the move e6, getting the same structure, but in a somewhat better version. The move a6 is anyway crucial in this structure, while White having delayed the g4 push, gets a lesser version of the same. } { It is also occasionally possible, with help of your opponent, to get the Scheveningen setup from some other Sicilian. For example, once I managed to get a good version against Fabiano from the Four Knights Sicilian @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.a3 e6 7.Be3 Be7 , where White committed to a3 rather early and needed extra moves to prepare the g4 push. } 
6. g4 {[%mdl 32768]} { It would be crazy to recommend something else. We have to 'punish' Black's move order. } h6 { This is the latest attempt by Black to revitalize the Scheveningen. From our point of view, it is just a bad version of the 6. h3 Najdorf though. } ( 6...Nc6 { This old move is really terrible. White gets the best version of this stuff. You can study it starting from here. [/variation/24623259] } ) ( 6...a6 { isn't good; with 7. h3? we could transpose to our Najdorf, but of course, this move would now be just useless. Instead, we thank our opponents for the tempo and crush - read the full analysis here [/variation/24623261]. } ) 
7. Rg1 ( { This is much more useful than going h3. The old mainline with } 7.h4 Nc6 8.Rg1 { is less challenging since Black has good chances to equalize after } 8...d5! { . } ) Nc6 ( 7...Be7 { Doesn't have much independent value, since } 8.Be3 Nc6 { will transpose to 7... Nc6 8. Be3 Be7. } ) 
8. Be3!? ( { This is the modern way of treating this line since the old } 8.h4 d5! { seems to likely hold for Black. With this move order, delaying the h-pawn push, we avoid the strike in the center. } ) a6 { The most often played move, but not a very good one. The modern Nxc6! solution works well here for White. } 
9. Nxc6 { Back in the day this idea was considered dubious, opening the b-file and reinforcing Black's center, but now we know that sometimes it can just be really strong. Black lacks actual counterplay and we have a free hand on the kingside. The b-file alone can't do us much harm. } bxc6 
10. Qf3 {[%cal Ge1c1]} Rb8 
11. O-O-O Qa5 
12. Bc4! {[%cal Gc4b3,Gh2h4]} { The bishop on b3 will block all the fun for Black and next we start crushing on the kingside. } *

