1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 g6 { The 'normal' Dragon starting position. } 
6. Be3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Those who have my Dragon LTR course would know that I am certainly going to recommend the Yugoslav Attack, the only principled option against the Dragon. White can also start with } 6.f3 { , but you really have to go for } ) ( 6.Be3 { and grab the extra } 6...Ng4?? 7.Bb5+ { odds along.

Now Black should objectively go for the mainline with Bg7/O-O/Nc6 in some order, but many, for understandable reasons, have tried some funky move orders to get the good old Dragon fun going. For us, it is pretty ridiculous to worry about that, since in 6. h3 g6 Najdorf we were an option for worse versions of such stuff and were still happy there. Nonetheless, I will cover these sidelines one by one here as well. } ) Bg7 ( 6...Ng4?? { Hundreds have fallen for this trap. } 7.Bb5+! { And Black loses material. } ) 
7. f3 O-O 
8. Qd2 Nc6 { The only sensible move, intending d5, which, if played directly, would allow e5. } 
9. O-O-O ( { I have worked very hard to make Dragon played and made an LTR course about it. I still believe Dragon to hold, but I noticed Black is still struggling in the over-the-board games in the mainline that I recommended after } 9.O-O-O { , so that is also what I am going to recommend. Against } ) ( 9.Bc4 { I recommended Nxd4 and Be6, while against } ) ( 9.g4 { it is important to go } 9...Be6! { . Both are quite worked out in my course and I can't offer much news there. } ) Bd7 { A common mistake at the lower level. Black goes for the plan that used to be playable against Bc4-Bb3 setup, but here with White not having lost time to regroup the bishop, the whole idea of Rc8 Ne5-Nc4 is way too slow. } 
10. g4 Rc8 
11. Kb1 Ne5 
12. Be2 ( { We can return Black one tempo. } 12.h4 h5 13.gxh5 { is also possible, though slightly messier. } ) Nc4 ( { It's not clear how else to generate counterplay. } 12...b5 { we can just collect with } 13.Ncxb5 { . } ) 
13. Bxc4 Rxc4 { This is a theoretical position with Black to move, in the variation where instead of Be2, we played Bc4-Bb3. Even there, by the way, Black wasn't equalizing fully. Now, we are cruising. } 
14. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]} h5 
15. gxh5 { We don't want to close the kingside obviously. Capturing the pawn deflects the knight from the center anyway. } Nxh5 
16. Rhg1 {[%cal Gg1g5]} { We are the only side with play here. Black's counterplay is completely nonexistent. } Kh7 
17. Qd3 Rc8 
18. Rg5 {[%cal Gc3d5,Gd4f5]} { We will throw in something forward and sac at some point. Black has nothing at all to offer, in the counterplay department. } *

