4. Nxd4 g6 { We can also get this position via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 g6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nc6 move order. In both cases, White could have avoided it, with a Rossolimo against 2... Nc6 - 3. Bb5, and with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 g6 and now for example 3.c3 or 3.d4 cxd4 4.Qxd4!? . That said, we are happy to get it and embrace the Maroczy bind setup. } 
5. c4 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Trying to transpose to the Dragon with } 5.Nc3 Bg7 6.Be3 { is not a fun mission, since Black gets a lot of good extra options in this so-called Accelerated Dragon compared to the standard Dragon. Instead, I propose to grab the space and go for the Maroczy bind, which is known to pose Black a lot of problems, as they are often stuck to the passive defense moving around mainly on the last three ranks.

Black has a few systems now, the most popular ones being early Nxd4 capture, forcing Qxd4, before we get the bishop to e3, the quick Bg7 Qb6 setup, trying to dislodge our knight from d4 and the old mainline, where Black just develops with Bg7 O-O d6 Bd7 and lets us finish our development undisturbed as well. There is also the old line @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppp1p/2n3p1/8/2PNP3/8/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq c3 0 5@@EndFEN@@ 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 Bg7 7.Be3 Ng4 , but although it looks cool, it's not very good. } ) Nf6 
6. Nc3 d6 ( { This is a clever move order, for } 6...Nxd4!? { which is clever as well (6... Bg7 is the not clever one), we go } 7.Qxd4 d6 { and can just transpose with } 8.Be2 { . } ) 
7. Be2 ( { We don't have the time for } 7.Be3 { now because of } 7...Ng4 { . } ) Bg7 { This is the standard old Maroczy. I guess the advantage of this line is that it's easy to play the initial first moves for Black and that there is a limit to how bad it can be. At the same time, it's really not a fun position and White has to barely know anything to get an opening advantage, which is rare nowadays in most of the openings. } 
8. Be3! { Of course, we have to guard the knight now. } O-O 
9. O-O Bd7 ( { This is by far the main move here. } 9...Nxd4 { it only makes sense to start with this if Black is worried about @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/2np1np1/8/2PNP3/2N1B3/PP2BPPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 5 9@@EndFEN@@ 9...Bd7 10.Nc2!? , but we don't do that. @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PnP3/2N1B3/PP2BPPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 10.Bxd4 Bd7 we can just transpose here with 11.Re1 , at the very least. } ) 
10. Re1 { Having gone through the old theory with Qd2 f3 and having realized that modern computers don't approve of the old wisdom, I have decided to just roll with the times and go for what the engines do like. } Nxd4 
11. Bxd4 Bc6 
12. Qc2 { Very unusual setup, but we don't fear the trade of bishops and don't want to weaken our dark squares unnecessarily with f3. } a5 
13. b3 Nd7 
14. Bxg7 Kxg7 
15. Rad1 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb3b4,Gh2h4]} { We have a beautiful position. The side with more space almost never has the issue of a bad bishop (interesting fun-fact that I only heard recently and I believe it makes sense!). On the other hand, we have a free hand here and can choose where to play. I do think it will likely be kingside with an h4!? eventually, but I can also see merit in one day going for a3-b4. } *

