10. Qd3 { I have played this against Magnus Carlsen and even though I didn't win the game because of the opening, I won the game and so far, the opening was also alright. } a5 { Carlsen played this against me, which is a standard idea in this system. } 
11. Be3 Bd7 ( { We allow } 11...Ng4 { as } 12.Bxg4 Bxg4 13.a4! { will be a favorable long-term edge due to our space advantage, and Black will have to give up the bishop pair shortly to keep our initiative at bay. } ) 
12. b3 ( { I showed a lack of understanding here by going for } 12.Bd4 { anyway, but then Black played Bc6 Nd7 and had better dark square control than if he had gone a4. Instead, I could have gone for the old-style setup here with b3 and f3. } ) Bc6 
13. f3 { The good old setup. } Nd7 
14. Rac1 { The rook is well placed here. } Nc5 
15. Qd2 { Funny enough, this position could also arise from the old main-line, with Bg7 without Nxd4. } Qb6 
16. Nb5! {[%cal Gb6b4]} { It's important to stop the idea of Qb4. }Rfc8 ( { We would be happy to see } 16...Bxb5 17.cxb5 { as that is a favorable structure change for us. We will follow it up with Rfd1, Bc4 and eventually likely with an a3-b4 break kicking away the knight. } ) 
17. Rfd1 {[%cal Ge2f1,Gg2g3,Gf3f4]} { Black is usually waiting around here and White does the same but eventually may try to prepare some expansion, with f4. Really eventually. First some maneuvring, with Bf1 g3 Bg2 being an idea. } *

