4. Nxd4 e5 
5. Nb5 d6 { The Kalashnikov is a sibling of the Sveshnikov Sicilian, but Black is usually then trying to avoid the mainline and keep the positions messier. } 
6. N1c3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { It is also possible to use the move order that Black played and go for } 6.c4!? { , but we are okay with a transposition to Sveshnikov Sicilian and I don't think the Kalashnikov sidelines are too bothersome. } ) ( 6.c4 { is also not so simple, with Black having multiple setups and counterplay attempts. } ) a6 ( { For } 6...Nf6 { see the Sveshnikov Sicilian. } ) 
7. Na3 b5 ( { Here after } 7...Nf6 8.Bg5 { we transpose to our Sveshnikov system, but Black has few other options here, that they usually also go for, else it makes little sense to start with 4... e5 and not 4... Nf6 right away. There is 7... b5, 7... Be7 and 7... Be6. } ) 
8. Nd5 ( { We could also try to transpose to our Sveshnikov system with } 8.Nab1 { hoping for } 8...Nf6 9.Bg5 { , but I propose to play more principled. Here Black has three options, Nf6, Nge7 and Nce7. } ) Nf6 ( { This is the healthiest option. } 8...Nge7 { will transpose to 8... Nf6 for us, but it also allows an extra option of 9. Bd3!?. } 9.c4 Nd4 10.cxb5 Nxd5 11.exd5 { transpose to the current line. } ) 
9. c4 ( 9.Bg5 { transposes to the mainline of the Sveshnikov, but one that we don't play. The text move is the more principled option and I used it myself against Radjabov to get a good position. } )b4 { We leave the e-pawn hanging, but 9...Nxe4 10.cxb5 Nd4 11.b6! would be excellent news for us. } ( 9...Nd4 { This will just transpose. } 10.cxb5 Nxd5 11.exd5 { transposes to 9... Nxd5. } ) 
10. Nc2!? { Sacrificing the e4-pawn. } a5 { Not taking the pawn isn't good, but Radjabov got away with it against me. } 
11. Bg5 { We will now follow my game [/variation/25632034] against Radjabov. } Be7 
12. Nxe7 Qxe7 
13. Ne3 -- ( { Both sides play the most natural moves, you can find the full analysis of the position after } 13...Be6 14.Bxf6 Qxf6 15.Qxd6 { in Chapter 8 [/variation/24987892]. } )
