1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 d6 { The Classical Sicilian is known as an extremely fighting weapon for Black, but also highly strategically dubious. Black often accepted doubled f-pawns and was hoping the long-term effect of the bishop pair would compensate. Nowadays, the opening has been researched a lot deeper than before and things have become a lot more concrete and less strategic. As you will see in the mainlines, some theoretical lines go deep into an endgame where the most fun for Black is gone. } 
6. Bg5 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { I will recommend the Rauzer, which is by far the main response against the Classical Sicilian. People also try } 6.Bc4 { and } ) ( 6.f3 { and there are some other sidelines, but they are all relatively harmless. Going for @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp2pppp/2np1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.h3 e5 7.Nf3 is possible, but it is very different from the Najdorf, since Black has saved a tempo on the move a6, but has determined the knight to c6 already. Having looked at that option, I decided to let it go, and keep 6. h3 against Najdorf and go for the main line, the Rauzer against the Classical Sicilian. } ) e6 { The main move. Black has a bunch of options on this and on the next couple of moves as well. } 
7. Qd2 ( { The main and the most harmonious move. The modern } 7.Qd3 { has some merit, as the queen can swing across to g3, and there is also @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2nppn2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ 7.Bb5!? first and only after 7...Bd7 8.Qd3!? , which I actually played in some rapid game against MVL. That is all fun, but I propose the established mainline because, in a healthier position, it is easier to make good moves. } ) Be7 { This is the old way of playing, naturally Black would try to finish the kingside development first, but turns out it's not that great. } 
8. O-O-O { Black can still transpose to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2nppn2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPPQ1PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@ 7...a6 8.O-O-O Be7 with a6 here, but for that see 7... a6 move order. } O-O { Taking on d4 first doesn't have much independent value, since Black can take on the next move. } 
9. h4!? ( { Actually, the main theoretical } 9.f4 { is also giving Black hell, but then they usually play out 10 more moves of old theory and feel smart about themselves. Instead, I propose a fresh move, which is just as good but will most likely take them by surprise right away. } ) Nxd4 { This is the best attempt by Black. } 
10. Qxd4 Qa5 { The most often played move, using the analogy from the 9. f4 variation, where this move does make sense. Here, however, the queen is just misplaced. } 
11. Kb1 { A standard move that is always useful in these sharp Sicilians. } Rd8 ( { Trying to make sense of Qa5. } 11...Bd7 12.Qd2 { is also unsatisfactory when Black has nothing better than retreating with the queen. } ) 
12. Qd2 { The queen anyway belongs here, but now we also create a threat of Nd5!. } Qc7 
13. Bd3 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2d4,Gf2f3,Gg2g4]} { And now in some order, we want to just play our thematic Bd3, f3, g4, Ne2-Nd4 setup, having just won a tempo thanks to Black's Qa5-Qc7 sortie. I gave a sample line starting from here. You can find it in Chapter 10 [/variation/26100344]. } *

