[ECO "B41"]

1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 e6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 a6 
5. c4 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { The Sicilian Kan is not a bad opening, but when played with aggressive intentions, it probably is. Back in the day, it was a way to get the opponents out of the book early and try to steer the game to a complicated middlegame leaving all the pieces on the board. However, as } 5.c4!? { line emerged, Black started facing a big dilemma. Are they going to fight for a draw with no winning chances, or are they ready to take the risk and go for a very dangerous version of the passive hedgehog structure? } ) ( { This line has become very popular, particularly after Carlsen used it to beat Anand in the World Championship [/variation/26063177] match in 2014. Back in the day, Black was usually permitted to get a Sicilian-type play after } 5.Nc3 { or } ) ( 5.Bd3 { , but the } ) ( 5.c4 { trend has discouraged many players who used Kan as a fighting weapon. } ) Nf6 ( { Black can also start with } 5...Qc7 { ( } 6.Nc3 Nf6 { transpose), but there is no point in delaying 5... Nf6. } ) 
6. Nc3 Qc7 ( { Here is a big moment for Black. The preferred choice of the engines, } 6...Bb4 { leads to very one-sided positions where Black tries to grind out a draw, while } ) ( 6...Qc7 { going for a hedgehog is really not liked by modern engines. Besides the hedgehog being a very passive setup in general, there are new trends with White going for more aggressive setups than the short castle. } ) ( { The most popular move, not surprisingly, since the Kan players are too desperate to get their hedgehog and don't want to start defending with } 6...Bb4 7.Qd3 d5 { . } ) 
7. a3 { We take the time to prevent Bb4. } b6 { The most respected move order here. Now White has a few different setups. } 
