[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's 1. e4  -  Part 3"]
[White "Najdorf Overview"]
[Black "Najdorf Overview"]
[Date "2023.03.29"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/24577317"]
[ECO "B90"]

1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 a6 { The Najdorf is no doubt the biggest challenge that a 1. e4 player can face when preparing against the Sicilians. As I had mentioned in my infamous Najdorf course, it is the soundest of all the sharp openings and the sharpest of all the sound ones. The fact that I am now on the other side of it, doesn't change any of that and yet, I am quite happy with the repertoire I would like to propose. }
6. h3 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5][%csl Gh3]} ( { While the recommended } 6.h3 { is by no means new, the follow up after the most common reply } 6...e5 { , } 7.Nf3!? { that I want to propose, is certainly very fresh. } ) { The idea of this move, which has been brought into the top-level practice by Bobby Fischer and that has been revitalized a decade or two ago, is very blunt. White wants to prepare the g4 push and play a Keres Attack (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e6 6.g4 ) with the extra move 6. h3. While it is not the most obvious move, since we are not developing either of our bishops yet, it is by now an established and well-respected variation.

It turns out the early kingside advance with h3-g4 is quite challenging and although Black has quite a few playable options against the 6. h3 system, in all of them, they really have to know what they are doing. Black generally chooses between the Fischeresque 6... e5 (which is also what I recommend for Black in my Najdorf course), the Scheveningen style 6... e6 and Dragon style 6... g6.

Also possible is to delay that decision with 6... Nc6 and there is also a premature looking 6... b5, that was trendy at some point, but does seem dubious after all. I should also mention that within 6... e6 setup, Black has various different setups, since after 7. g4 it is possible to go for 7... d5!?, 7... h6!?, as well as finishing the development with 7... Be7 (or 7... Nfd7 first), all of which are very different in nature.

As you had already understood by now, there is a lot of work for us ahead, so let's jump straight into it. } e5 { The most popular move and the most Najdorf-style option, especially if you play the Najdorf in Fischer style, which is trying to play e5 whenever possible and not how Kasparov played it at some point in the 80's, when his concept was to go for the e6 Scheveningen setups everywhere. This is also what I recommend in my course. } ( { • } 6...b5 { This looks premature, since usually in the Najdorf, before this thematic queenside expansion, Black first prepares it with moves like e6 and sometimes even Nbd7. Although it has experiences some popularity, it seems after all, that Black queenside is very vulnerable here to some poking with 7. a4!. } ) ( { • } 6...Nc6 { This move is neither here nor there, but is very playable. Black keeps both options of e5 and g6 open, remaining flexible. The idea is to meet 7.g4 with g6, and 7.Be3 with e5, trying to move order us somewhat. Fortunately we have a solution for this little move order puzzle. } ) ( { • } 6...g6 { The Dragon, or rather the Dragodorf setup is in fact very reasonable here. White's ideal setup against the Dragon is the Yugoslav Attack with Be3 f3 Qd2, and so the move h3 is somewhat out of place here. That said, the Dragon is a very risky opening and the extra move a6 that Black has here is not of tremendous use either. } ) ( { • } 6...e6 { This Scheveningen style push makes a lot of sense here, now that White has spent a tempo preparing g4 push with h3. Compared to the pure Scheveningen Keres Attack which is 5... e6 6. g4, Black clearly has the better version, since a6 is extremely useful, while h3 may turn out to be somewhat of a waste of a tempo. That said, the pure Scheveningen is so terrible, that even up a tempo, Black is facing serious challenges down the road here. } 7.g4 { The planned push, now Black is at another crossroads. } 7...d5 { An attempt to equalize in the most direct fashion. There is also some ancient chess wisdom that says that one must reply to an attack on a flank with a blow in the center. At the same time, there is also the Stockfish engine which says that White remains slightly better in these systems. A lot of things to consider, basically. } { 7...b5 I believe this used to be the main way to go, until White discovered, around the time that I started playing chess professionally, that there is a strong idea to sacrifice the c3 knight with Nd5!? down the line. Nowadays it is therefore considered dubious. }{ 7...Nc6?! Determining the knight to c6 is just inflexible and not very good. Black should instead go for 7... Be7 or 7... Nfd7 first, which are the moves Black needs to play anyway and wait with Nc6 for now, keeping the option of b5 as well. Only after White goes for Bg2, anticipating the b5 push, should Black then go for Nc6. }{ 7...h6 In modern chess, where the engines really appreciate space and therefore also appreciate preventing opponents from gaining space, this move is highly respected. }{ 7...Nfd7 This is extremely flexible and even though it looks highly unnatural to move an already developed piece, without having any other piece developed, it appears to be a very decent move order. It may not be necessarily worse than starting with 7...Be7. }{ 7...Be7 A natural developing move, keeping the queenside flexible and embracing the g4-g5 push. }) 
7. Nf3!? {[%cal Gg2g4,Gf3g5,Gg4g5]} { This relatively rare move is the heart of our Anti-Najdorf repertoire. This line didn't quite exist when I was making my Najdorf course and I managed to successfully introduce it against MVL in Wijk aan Zee 2021 and later I used it again against Wei Yi, gaining a big opening advantage there as well.

Usually systems with Nf3 are very timid, as the knight blocks the f2 pawn and White often played this move with the intention to slowly develop with Bc4, O-O and play around the d5 square. I have spent half of my Najdorf course explaining how to battle this timid strategy and that is certainly not the plan I want to propose here. Our intentions are in fact very direct and aggressive, as we intend to launch the g2 pawn forward to g4 and beyond and use the f3 knight as support. } *

