8. exd5 ( { The main move and the one I would like to recommend, even though there are interesting alternatives for White, such as } 8.Nde2!? { . } ) Nxd5 
9. Nde2 {[%csl Rd5]} { The way to play for White, challenging the knight on d5. Now Black has a bunch of options, in all of which equality is in sight, but nothing seems quite comfortable for Black either. Another important thing to keep in mind, is that the positions are often one-sided, which is something let's say the Berlin or the Petroff players would accept, but not what the Najdorf boys are in here for. } Bb4 { This used to be the main move and is by far the most played one according to my database. Black develops the kingside first. } 
10. Bg2 ( { There is a clever option of } 10.a3!? { as well, which I believe I wasn't aware of, back in the day when this line was hype. } ) O-O 
11. O-O { Now Black has two options. At some point taking with the bishop was supposed to equalize, but then White discovered a pawn sacrifice that keeps the fire burning. Taking with the knight instead, always looked slightly worse for Black. The main issue Black is facing in these positions is the bishop on c8, which looks very miserable compared to our fianchettoed monster on g2. } Nxc3 
12. Nxc3 Qc7 { Black keeps the queens on the board, in hope to develop the c8 bishop. } 
13. Qd4 Bd6 { This is a decent alternative for Black, apparently recommended by GM Hoffman in his Chessable course. } 
14. Ne4 {[%mdl 32768]} Be7 ( { The move of Hoffman, if } 14...Be5 { then } 15.Qc5! { keeps the initiative going, as we always welcome the endgames, thanks to our superior light-squared bishop. } ) 
15. Qc3 { I love the look of this move and the fact that the machines love it too. We anticipate Nc6 and offer a trade of queens. Unfortunately it is not exactly a novelty though, since it has been played in a corr. game: Steiger-Muri [/variation/29098198], 2017. } Nc6 { Endgames are no good, as the bishop on c8 is so bad. The text move is Black's best bet. } 
16. b3 { Intending to develop the bishop to the long diagonal, finishing the development. } e5 
17. Bb2 Bb4 { We are following the aforementioned corr. game. } 
18. Qg3 { The queen sits excellently on this square. } f5 { Black tries to free the position somewhat, but the problem with this otherwise excellent push, is that now the e5 pawn becomes isolated and the square in front of it becomes an outpost. } 
19. gxf5 Bxf5 
20. Rad1 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gb2c1,Gg1h2,Gf1g1][%csl Ge4]} { Our knight on e4 is absolutely gorgeous. I like the idea of going c3 next, taking away the d4 square from the c6 knight and then redeploying our dark squared bishop with Bc1. The semi-open g-file is not an issue for us at the moment, as the bishop on g2 is there and Black doesn't have a rook lift available here. Potentially we may also try using the g-file for ourselves with ideas such as Kh2 and Rg1, eventually. } *

