1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 e6 { The Scheveningen Sicilian was a very respectable opening for a very long time. It is a sound setup with a sound pawn structure, but in this particular version of it, the pure Scheveningen, so-called, White gets an opportunity to go for the direct 6. g4! called the Keres Attack.

For the Scheveningen fans, I recommend playing the Najdorf and only after White makes a developing move on move 6, such as 6. h3 (or 6. Be3, 6. Be2, 6. f3 etc) to only then play the move e6, getting the same structure, but in a somewhat better version. The move a6 is anyway crucial in this structure, while White having delayed the g4 push, gets a lesser version of the same. } { It is also occasionally possible, with help of your opponent, to get the Scheveningen setup from some other Sicilian. For example, once I managed to get a good version against Fabiano from the Four Knights Sicilian @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.a3 e6 7.Be3 Be7 , where White committed to a3 rather early and needed extra moves to prepare the g4 push. } 
6. g4 { It would be crazy to recommend something else. We have to 'punish' Black's move order. } e5 { This was an attempt at some point, to force the issue and try to solve the problems in complications. It seems though, that given accurate play by White, this doesn't equalize. } 
7. Nf5! ( { The much more tempting } 7.Bb5+ { is where actually Black manages to get much closer to equality. } ) g6 ( { This has been played a few times as well and is in fact the top choice of my engines, since they discard the main move } 7...h5 { and look for a playable alternative instead. } ) 
8. Ne3 {[%mdl 32768]} Nc6 { Black is trying to finish the development and hopes to get away with the weak d5 square, like in some other Sicilians. } 
9. h4!? { Keeping the options open, we might go g5, we might also go h5!?. } Be6 { Keeping the f8 bishop flexible for now. } 
10. h5!? ( { It is also possible to go for } 10.g5 { and sit on d5 square, but Black will try to get some counterplay there, with well-timed Nf4!? ideas. } ) Be7 { A sample line. } 
11. Bg2 {[%cal Gc3d5][%csl Ge4]} { Intending Ncd5. } Qd7 { Black can try to castle long, now that the pawn on h5 is intimidating. } 
12. f3 O-O-O 
13. Ned5 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gd1d2,Ge1c1]} { We also plan to finish our development. Black doesn't seem to have enough play in return for our dominance over the d5 square. } Kb8 
14. Be3 gxh5 { Trying to get some play. } 
15. g5 Ne8 
16. Qd2 f5 
17. gxf6 Nxf6 
18. O-O-O {[%csl Gd5,Rh5,Rh7]} { Some things happened, but we kept the dominance over the d5 square. White is better and the h5 pawn is of course doomed to fall one day, when the other h-pawn will also be weak. } *

