For the Scheveningen fans, I recommend playing the Najdorf and only after White makes a developing move on move 6, such as 6. h3 (or 6. Be3, 6. Be2, 6. f3 etc) to only then play the move e6, getting the same structure, but in a somewhat better version. The move a6 is anyway crucial in this structure, while White having delayed the g4 push, gets a lesser version of the same. } { It is also occasionally possible, with help of your opponent, to get the Scheveningen setup from some other Sicilian. For example, once I managed to get a good version against Fabiano from the Four Knights Sicilian @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.a3 e6 7.Be3 Be7 , where White committed to a3 rather early and needed extra moves to prepare the g4 push. } 
6. g4 { It would be crazy to recommend something else. We have to 'punish' Black's move order. } e5 { This was an attempt at some point, to force the issue and try to solve the problems in complications. It seems though, that given accurate play by White, this doesn't equalize. } 
7. Nf5! ( { The much more tempting } 7.Bb5+ { is where actually Black manages to get much closer to equality. } ) h5 { This was supposed to be the way for Black, but it leads to a very sad position by force. } 
8. Bg5! {[%mdl 32768]} { At some point the computers started showing this strong sequence. } hxg4 
9. Nd5 Bxf5 { The line is semi-forced. } 
10. Bxf6 gxf6 
11. exf5 Bh6 {[%cal Gh6g5,Gh8h4]} { Black's dark-squared bishop gets some air but is shooting into emptiness. Here though is an important moment - we have to know one difficult move, to not let Black get decent chances with a dark-squared blockade. } 
12. h4! ( { This is very important. If } 12.c3? { which is the most natural and the most popular move, then after } 12...Bg5! { Black gets to activate the rook, which would turn things around and give Black a fully acceptable position. With this move, we limit Black's h8 rook and at a cost of a pawn, get ready to activate our own. } ) gxh3 ( { If } 12...Nd7 { or } ) ( 12...Nc6 { we just activate our rook with } 13.Rg1! { , picking up the g4-pawn. } ) 
13. Rxh3 Kf8 { This happened in Volokitin-Papp 2012. Here White has a few ways to improve on that game, but I particularly like the aesthetics of the engine's top choice on depth. } 
14. a4! { We do the same thing on the other side now! } Nc6 
15. Raa3 {[%cal Ga3g3,Gc2c3][%csl Ga3,Gh3]} { Beautiful double rook lift action! Our king is perfectly fine on e1 and we get two active rooks without having to castle at all. } *

