5. Nc3 e6 { The Scheveningen Sicilian was a very respectable opening for a very long time. It is a sound setup with a sound pawn structure, but in this particular version of it, the pure Scheveningen, so-called, White gets an opportunity to go for the direct 6. g4! called the Keres Attack.

For the Scheveningen fans, I recommend playing the Najdorf and only after White makes a developing move on move 6, such as 6. h3 (or 6. Be3, 6. Be2, 6. f3 etc) to only then play the move e6, getting the same structure, but in a somewhat better version. The move a6 is anyway crucial in this structure, while White having delayed the g4 push, gets a lesser version of the same. } { It is also occasionally possible, with help of your opponent, to get the Scheveningen setup from some other Sicilian. For example, once I managed to get a good version against Fabiano from the Four Knights Sicilian @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.a3 e6 7.Be3 Be7 , where White committed to a3 rather early and needed extra moves to prepare the g4 push. } 
6. g4 { It would be crazy to recommend something else. We have to 'punish' Black's move order. } h6 { This is the latest attempt by Black to revitalize the Scheveningen. From our point of view, it is just a bad version of the 6. h3 Najdorf though. } 
7. Rg1 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { This is much more useful than going h3. The old mainline with } 7.h4 Nc6 8.Rg1 { is less challenging since Black has good chances to equalize after } 8...d5! { . } ) Nc6 ( 7...Be7 { Doesn't have much independent value, since } 8.Be3 Nc6 { will transpose to 7... Nc6 8. Be3 Be7. } ) 
8. Be3!? ( { This is the modern way of treating this line since the old } 8.h4 d5! { seems to likely hold for Black. With this move order, delaying the h-pawn push, we avoid the strike in the center. } ) Bd7 { This is a decent attempt to mix things up. Black is trying to confuse us with the move orders. } 
9. Be2!? ( { The natural } 9.Qd2 { can me bet with . Instead, we wait for a move and overprotect g4 pawn, for Nxd4 e5 action. } ) Be7 { The most flexible, trying to finish the development. } 
10. Qd2 ( { Now this is good, since taking and e5 doesn't threaten the g4 pawn and we can retreat with the queen to a good square like d3 and not all the way to d1. Meanwhile } 10.h4 { is, as so often, met with } 10...d5! { . } ) Nxd4 
11. Qxd4 Bc6 { Played in a corr game from 2020. Black is trying to control some squares in the center and perhaps go for a d5 break one day. } 
12. O-O-O Qb6! { Moujan, P playing the top computer choices in his corr game from 2020. } 
13. Qc4!? ( { In Faure-Mojan, 2020 White went } 13.Qd2 Qd8! 14.Bd3 d5 { and Black came close to equalizing and eventually held. I propose another attempt. } ) Qa5 
14. a3 { Anticipating d5 and waiting for Black to show their cards. } Rd8 { Top choice, preparing d5. } 
15. Qd4 ( { We are trying to dance around with our queen as to not get hit by d5 at an unpleasant moment. Alternatively, I can suggest } 15.f4!? O-O 16.g5 d5 17.Qb3 { with complications, but with accurate play Black survives there in the end. } ) e5 ( { If Black plays } 15...a6 { we can proceed with } 16.h4 { . } ) 
16. Qd3 d5 { Black comes close to equalizing here, but we maintain some advantage after the simplifications. } 
17. exd5 Nxd5 
18. Nxd5 Rxd5 
19. Qb3 O-O 
20. Bc4 Rxd1+ 
21. Rxd1 {[%csl Gc4,Ge3]} { We have more active bishops and Black has to be very precise for a very long time, to hold this slightly worse position. } *

