5. Nc3 e6 { The Scheveningen Sicilian was a very respectable opening for a very long time. It is a sound setup with a sound pawn structure, but in this particular version of it, the pure Scheveningen, so-called, White gets an opportunity to go for the direct 6. g4! called the Keres Attack.

For the Scheveningen fans, I recommend playing the Najdorf and only after White makes a developing move on move 6, such as 6. h3 (or 6. Be3, 6. Be2, 6. f3 etc) to only then play the move e6, getting the same structure, but in a somewhat better version. The move a6 is anyway crucial in this structure, while White having delayed the g4 push, gets a lesser version of the same. } { It is also occasionally possible, with help of your opponent, to get the Scheveningen setup from some other Sicilian. For example, once I managed to get a good version against Fabiano from the Four Knights Sicilian @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.a3 e6 7.Be3 Be7 , where White committed to a3 rather early and needed extra moves to prepare the g4 push. } 
6. g4 { It would be crazy to recommend something else. We have to 'punish' Black's move order. } h6 { This is the latest attempt by Black to revitalize the Scheveningen. From our point of view, it is just a bad version of the 6. h3 Najdorf though. } 
7. Rg1 ( { This is much more useful than going h3. The old mainline with } 7.h4 Nc6 8.Rg1 { is less challenging since Black has good chances to equalize after } 8...d5! { . } ) Nc6 ( 7...Be7 { Doesn't have much independent value, since } 8.Be3 Nc6 { will transpose to 7... Nc6 8. Be3 Be7. } ) 
8. Be3!? ( { This is the modern way of treating this line since the old } 8.h4 d5! { seems to likely hold for Black. With this move order, delaying the h-pawn push, we avoid the strike in the center. } ) Be7 
9. Qe2!? {[%cal Ge1c1][%csl Gg4]} ( { A healthy developing move, intending to meet } 9.h4 { with } 9...d5! { . Here White has a few options, but the engine and most games as well, go for @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp2bpp1/2nppn1p/8/3NP1P1/2N1B3/PPP2P1P/R2QKBR1 w Qkq - 4 9@@EndFEN@@ 9.Qe2!? , keeping an eye on the g4 pawn. } ) ( { More sophisticated than } 9.Qd2 { , which allows } 9...Nxd4 { and e5. Now we keep an eye on g4. Alternatively } ) ( 9.Nb3!? { is also liked by computers. } ) Nxd4 { Black changes the pawn structure, in order to get more play. } 
10. Bxd4 e5 
11. Be3 Be6 { The positions with a pawn on e5 are always less dangerous for Black than ones with a pawn on e6, but equality is not guaranteed. White can often diffuse all of Black's play with a well-timed Nd5. } 
12. O-O-O { Black has a couple of options here, but none seems to offer full equality. } Rc8 { The most principled move, but I haven't been able to fully make it work for Black. The complications do seem to favor White. } 
13. Qb5+! { This is important. We grab some pawns. } Nd7 
14. Qxb7!? ( { Here the problem for Black is that both, grabbing the b7-pawn, but also the simple } 14.Nd5!? { give White the advantage. } ) ( { This is ambitious and fun, but if you are lazy, I recommend } 14.Nd5 { with a pleasant advantage, thanks to domination on the light squares. } ) O-O { Spirited. } 
15. Qxa7!? {[%mdl 32768]} { Grabbing another pawn. Brave and strong. } Ra8 
16. Qb7 Bg5 { Black can't keep chasing the queen with the rook, since we will slide away, via a6. With this move, Black tries to get some dark squares. } 
17. Qb4 {[%cal Gf1b5,Ga2a4]} { Intending Bb5 and a4, cementing the queenside. Black has to go back with the bishop. } Be7 
18. Rd5!? Bxd5 ( { This is a cool exchange sac. We keep the knight on c3 and after } 18...Bxd5 19.exd5 { , we will solidify our queenside with Bb5 and a4. } ) 
19. exd5 Bg5 
20. Bb5 Bxe3+ 
21. fxe3 {[%cal Ga2a4]} { We have a huge majority on the queenside and our king is as safe as ever. White is better here. } *

