Now Black should objectively go for the mainline with Bg7/O-O/Nc6 in some order, but many, for understandable reasons, have tried some funky move orders to get the good old Dragon fun going. For us, it is pretty ridiculous to worry about that, since in 6. h3 g6 Najdorf we were an option for worse versions of such stuff and were still happy there. Nonetheless, I will cover these sidelines one by one here as well. } ) a6 { The so called Dragodorf, which can be played after Bg7 f3, or before, with subtle differences. } 
7. f3 { We can play in a similar fashion when Black delays Bg7 as well. This move h5 is very sensible in the Dragodorf, as Black tries to prevent both the Bh6 idea and also the g2-g4 push. However, this means that castling short now becomes very dangerous, so Black will have to play for a long time with the king in the center. } h5 ( { For } 7...Bg7 { see 6... Bg7 7. f3 a6, starting from here [/variation/25157431]. } ) 
8. Qd2 Nbd7 ( { This is kind of sensible, to try and delay Bg7, which actually even has a concrete point as we will see. If } 8...e5 9.Nb3 { Black played a normal variation of the Najdorf against the English attack with a very strange move g6 in there. White goes long castle and then can go for the f4 plan after Be2 or Bd3 and Rhf1. } ) 
9. Bc4 { The same setup as in the 6... Bg7 7. f3 a6 line works well here too. } b5 
10. Bd5!? { Clarifies the position and leads to an advantage for White. } Nxd5 
11. Nxd5 Bb7 
12. O-O-O {[%cal Ge3g5][%csl Re7,Gf8]} { Black can try delaying Bg7, not having to deal with Bg5, but at some point, the development will be needed. } Rc8 
13. Kb1 -- ( { It is becoming hard for Black to keep making useful moves that aren't Bg7. If } 13...Bg7 { , however, then } 14.Bg5! { regains us the bishop - see the 6... Bg7 7. f3 a6 lines [/variation/25157431] for such. } )
*

