1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 d6 { The most common move order to get to the 'normal' Dragon. } 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 g6 { The 'normal' Dragon starting position. } 
6. Be3 ( { Those who have my Dragon LTR course would know that I am certainly going to recommend the Yugoslav Attack, the only principled option against the Dragon. White can also start with } 6.f3 { , but you really have to go for } ) ( 6.Be3 { and grab the extra } 6...Ng4?? 7.Bb5+ { odds along.

Now Black should objectively go for the mainline with Bg7/O-O/Nc6 in some order, but many, for understandable reasons, have tried some funky move orders to get the good old Dragon fun going. For us, it is pretty ridiculous to worry about that, since in 6. h3 g6 Najdorf we were an option for worse versions of such stuff and were still happy there. Nonetheless, I will cover these sidelines one by one here as well. } ) Bg7 ( 6...Ng4?? { Hundreds have fallen for this trap. } 7.Bb5+! { And Black loses material. } ) 
7. f3 O-O 
8. Qd2 Nc6 { The only sensible move, intending d5, which, if played directly, would allow e5. } 
9. O-O-O ( { I have worked very hard to make Dragon played and made an LTR course about it. I still believe Dragon to hold, but I noticed Black is still struggling in the over-the-board games in the mainline that I recommended after } 9.O-O-O { , so that is also what I am going to recommend. Against } ) ( 9.Bc4 { I recommended Nxd4 and Be6, while against } ) ( 9.g4 { it is important to go } 9...Be6! { . Both are quite worked out in my course and I can't offer much news there. } ) d5 { This is definitely the way to go. Many players, those who don't know the modern theory, so either strong players of the past, or lesser experienced players of the present, went with the other, standard Dragon plans, such as Bd7 Rc8 or Nxd4 Be6, but here, with White not having wasted any time on Bc4, they are just too slow. From the alternatives, 9... h5 is the only one worthy of some more attention. } 
10. exd5 { I will recommend the mainline. I covered all the side-gigs for my Dragon LTR course - they aren't as testing. } Nxd5 
11. Nxc6 bxc6 
12. Bd4 e5 { This used to be the old mainline, but after my Dragon LTR, I personally consider it the new mainline as well. } 
13. Bc5 Be6 
14. Ne4 ( { You should by no means be tempted to take the offered exchange as after } 14.Bxf8? Qxf8 15.Nxd5 cxd5 { Black has more than enough compensation with their powerful bishops aiming at our king and both the rook and queen ready to swing to b-file to further pile on the pressure. } ) Re8 ( 14...Rb8 15.Bc4 Re8 16.g4 { is an improved version for White with similar ideas as in our line, whereas @@StartFEN@@ 1r1q1rk1/p4pbp/2p1b1p1/2Bnp3/2B1N3/5P2/PPPQ2PP/2KR3R b - - 5 15@@EndFEN@@ 15...f5?! is just trouble for Black after 16.Ng5 . } ) 
15. h4 h5 ( { This is better than the old } 15...h6?! { , when we can fully paralyze Black's kingside. } ) 
16. Bc4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf4 
17. Bxe6 Nxe6 ( { Black can try to hold the endgame after } 17...Qxd2+ 18.Rxd2 Nxe6 { , but it doesn't seem like fun - } 19.Be3 { and we still have the better pawn structure. } ) 
18. Qc3 Qb8 
19. b3 { White is better here, Black still can't push f5, because of Nd6, when Black is just too uncoordinated. } *

