7. Nb3 ( { There are some funky weird lines in } 7.Nb5 { , but I decided to recommend something extremely simple, taking the fun out of this. } ) Qd8 { Black's point is that our b3 knight will most likely need to go back to d4 at some point, so Qb6-Qd8 is not necessarily losing any time. } 
8. Qd2 ( { It is interesting and even more principled to go for } 8.Nc3 Bxc3!? 9.bxc3 { position, but that's probably what Black is hoping for, getting some unbalanced game. } ) Nf6 
9. f3 ( { Again, the cleanest option, since } 9.Nc3 Ng4!? { can get messy. } ) d6 
10. Nc3 ( { Very similar is } 10.Be2 { , it mostly transposes to each other. } ) O-O 
11. Be2 { We continue with the natural development. } a5 { Black can also use the fancy Qb6-Qd8 move order adventure, to try to grab space on the queenside directly. } 
12. Na4!? { We can slow down Black's counterplay. } Be6 ( { After } 12...Nd7 { , the computer proposes to suddenly switch gears - } 13.O-O-O!? { and go for h4/Bh6 style attack, using the fact that the f6 knight has left so carelessly. } ) 
13. Nb6 { We can just win a pawn here. } Rb8 { Black should do this and hope to somehow simplify the position a pawn down, rather than have the rook stuck on a7. } 
14. Nxa5 Nd7 
15. Nxd7 Qxd7 
16. Nxc6 bxc6 
17. Bd4 { Black has to work hard here to prove compensation for a full pawn. } *

