10. a4 ( { Also interesting is } 10.Bxf6!? gxf6 11.Bd3 { , but I like the idea of just transposing to our mainline. } ) Qa5!? ( { An extra option, but a very provocative one. } 10...b4 { The most natural move and the one that transposes to 9... Be7 eventually. } 11.Nd5 Be7 { Both sides have no alternative at this point. } 12.Bxf6 Bxf6 13.Bc4 O-O { see 9... Be7. } ) 
11. Bxf6 {[%csl Gd5]} { We have to get some control over the d5-square, since b4 was a threat. } gxf6 
12. Nd2 { Intending a positional pawn sac. } b4 
13. Nd5 { We give up the e4-pawn, but keep control of the d5-square nonetheless. } Bxd5 
14. exd5 Qxd5 
15. Nc4 Qxd1+ 
16. Rxd1 {[%cal Gg2a8,Gg2g3,Gf1g2][%csl Rd5,Rd6]} { We still have all the squares and now have an open long diagonal. } Nd4 { The best. } 
17. c3 bxc3 
18. bxc3 Ne6 
19. Ne3 {[%cal Gf1d3][%csl Ra6,Gd5,Rd6,Gf5,Rf6]} { With beautiful light square domination White is for choice, even though we are down a pawn in an endgame. It will not be a problem to regain the pawn at some point, as Black's pawns are all weak. } *

