1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 e5 { The Sveshnikov is one of the biggest challenges for an Open Sicilian player, like ourselves. In fact, the opening is so sound that nowadays many top players have shifted to the sidelines such as 3. Bb5 Rossolimo to look for ways to challenge it. Luckily, already for a couple of years, I was aware of a little idea in the old mainline, which I am happy to present to you here in my course. Fortunately, the idea is still not too well known, to be quite poisonous and promising for White, no wonder some high-level games started to appear there as well. } 
6. Ndb5 d6 
7. Bg5 ( { It would be logical to recommend } 7.Nd5 { which is considered to be the most challenging ever since the Caruana-Carlsen encounters from their 2018 World Championship Match. However, that is by now quite explored as well and what I am going to recommend instead is a lot fresher, and if Black is unprepared - no less critical. } ) a6 
8. Na3 b5 
9. Nab1!? ( { This is extremely rare. The tabia is known for two major directions, } 9.Bxf6 { and } ) ( 9.Nd5 { and almost everyone overlooks that there is a third possibility. We immediately deal with the main issue in our position - the knight on the rim. I had first heard about this system from a friend of mine, two years ago, but recently it has again been brought to my attention when I saw Pichot using it against Grischuk in a very prestigious game and I also saw a very insightful string of tweets about it from ICCF IM Ntirlis. } ) Be7 { The main move but not the only one. } 
10. Bxf6 {[%csl Gd5]} ( { We have to give up our dark-squared bishop to gain full control over the d5-square. Note that we don't start with } 10.a4? b4 { because of the } 11.Bxf6 bxc3 { intermezzo. } ) Bxf6 
11. a4 {[%csl Gc4]} { Gaining access to c4-square before launching the knight to d5. } b4 { This looks automatic, but there are alternatives, in fact. } 
12. Nd5 O-O ( { A lot of moves transpose to each other now. If Black starts } 12...Bg5 { then after } 13.Bc4 { the castle will anyway have to happen. } ) 
13. Bc4 Bg5 ( { Again, all roads lead to Rome - if Black starts } 13...Be6 { after } 14.O-O { , the move } 14...Bg5 { will come anyway, so it all transposes. } ) 
14. O-O Be6 ( { Here in fact is a big juncture. Most games go with Kh8 with idea f5, while the engines prefer the developing } 14...Be6 { . } ) { The computer's choice. We still go for c3 idea, but here Black hasn't wasted time on Kh8. } 
15. Qd3 a5 { This weakens the b5-square, but at least Black gets rid of the weakness on a6 and prevents a potential b4 expansion later on, after an eventual c3 bxc3 Nbxc3 pawn structure change. } 
16. c3 Rc8 ( { This is more cunning than } 16...Rb8 { , also preventing } 17.cxb4 { , since after } 17...Nxb4 { the c4 bishop is under pressure. } ) 
17. Rd1 { We make a useful move for now. } bxc3 { Top choice of Stockfish, at least on some depth. The evaluation is dropping towards the floor, but the position still doesn't feel entirely equal to me, as we are the ones sitting on the weak square and can decide at what point do we want to get some action going. } 
18. Nbxc3 {[%mdl 32768]} Nb4 
19. Qe2 h5 { Possibly a useful move, but not sure it does much. } 
20. h3 g6 
21. b3 {[%csl Gb3,Gc4,Gd5]} { A standard idea in this system, strengthening our light square control, by defending the c4 bishop. } Nxd5 
22. Nxd5 {[%cal Gd1d3,Ga1d1][%csl Gc4,Gd5]} { We will sit on the d5-square and long term will try to either try and trade the light-squared bishop or/and perhaps get b4 at some point. Is won't be easy against accurate play, as the engine is able to prevent it, but waiting doesn't seem fun for Black, with no active ideas at all at this point, since I believe f5 is more likely counterproductive, only creating more weaknesses without getting a realistic chance at a kingside counterplay. } *

