8. Bb5 { This is an important move, we develop with tempo, but also disconnect the Black queen from the d6 pawn. } Bd7 
9. Qd2 ( { Against Rapport in a very important game for me I played the simple } 9.Bc4!? Bg7 10.Nxc6 Bxc6 11.O-O O-O 12.Qd3 { and got a very tiny advantage that with some luck I managed to successfully convert. That said, objectively, White has more challenging ways to play and I will recommend one such. } ) Bg7 
10. O-O-O {[%csl Rd6]} { Castling long has the advantage that we don't need to waste time to double on the d-file and pressure the d6 pawn. } O-O 
11. Nb3 {[%csl Rd6]} { We are coming for the d6-pawn. } a6 { Black's best bet to try and simplify, according to the computer. } 
12. Bxc6 {[%mdl 32768]} { We part with another bishop, but will claim the d6 pawn. } Bxc6 
13. f3! {[%cal Rf6f5]} { There is no rush to take the d6 pawn and it's important to prevent f5. } a5 { Black should look for counterplay by pushing the side pawn. } 
