8. O-O-O Bd7 ( { There are many options here, though nowadays at the highest level only } 8...Bd7 { and sometimes } ) ( 8...Be7 { is seen. Understandably, since the other moves are hated by the engines. } ) { This is the ultimate mainline of the Classical Sicilian Rauzer. There are many games here, old, new, top level, amateurs, everything. White generally has two different directions here. One is to go for f4 which usually leads to Bxf6 gxf6 structures down the road and another is to play a move like 9. f3 (or the modern 9. Kb1!?) and play the Scheveningen style position, resembling the English Attack in the e6 Najdorf. I propose the second path, but with a wrinkle, starting with 9. Kb1!? first. } 
9. Kb1 ( { This is a clever move order attempt. We want to transpose to } 9.f3 { when it suits us and not transpose when it doesn't. I should also mention @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p1b1ppp/p1nppn2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPPQ1PPP/2KR1B1R w kq - 2 9@@EndFEN@@ 9.Nxc6!? Bxc6 10.f3 played by Nepo, which can either transpose to my recommendation after 10...Be7 , or lead to a very safe endgame after 10...h6! 11.Bf4 d5 12.Qe1 Bb4 13.a3 Bxc3 14.Qxc3 O-O 15.Be5 Rc8 16.Bxf6 Qxf6 17.Qxf6 gxf6 18.exd5 Bxd5 19.Rd4 . Nepo used this line to get a safe position against Rapport in the Candidates, when in a must-draw situation, but it's hard to get something going in that endgame with White against a good defense, so I chose not to recommend it for the ambitious players out there. } ) Nxd4 { This is the latest word of theory. Black starts with Nxd4. Apparently, the queen is better placed on d2 than on d4 anyway, while the bishop on d7 is not so well placed on c6. Compared to Nxc6 Bxc6, surprisingly, Nxd4 Qxd4 is the way for Black to gain half a tempo. Counterintuitive, but true, as the engines confirm. } 
10. Qxd4 Be7 ( { Including } 10...h6 11.Bh4 { is not really in Black's favor. } ) 
11. f4 { The most principled and the most direct challenge. However, since if Black knows everything, the position can get simplified into a rather drawish endgame, so along with this, I also propose an entirely new idea [/variation/24987963], that has not been mentioned or played anywhere so far. } Bc6 { Pretty much the only adequate response to the threat of e5. } 
12. f5 Qa5! { This is an important move, forcing the issue. Black must know the ins and outs here though, as my game against Abdusattorov showed. } 
13. Bc4 { The start of a long forced (for Black, because we have options!) sequence. } exf5 
14. Rhf1 { The most challenging move. } fxe4 ( { Bailing out with } 14...Qe5? { is not good, } 15.Qxe5 dxe5 16.Rxf5 { and Black has a bad endgame. } ) 
15. Nxe4 { This is a big moment. It is wild to take with the knight here with Black, but if they know, they know. My opponent Abdusattorov, though, forgot. } Nxe4! { A brave move, but the only one. The problem is that a well prepared opponent might know it. } 
16. Qxg7 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Super scary stuff is } 16.Bxf7+!? { and also @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1p2bppp/p1bp4/q5B1/2BQn3/8/PPP3PP/1K1R1R2 w kq - 0 16@@EndFEN@@ 16.Bxe7!? Kxe7 17.Rxf7+ . You can definitely check those out, it may be worth a shot. } ) O-O-O! { Black returns material but gets the king to safety. } 
17. Bxe7 Nd2+ { Forcing more simplfications. } 
18. Rxd2 { Moving the king is similar. } Qxd2 
19. Bxd8 Rxd8 { Here White has a few options, since we are slightly better, but with accurate defense Black should be able to hold this, because the position is really simplified. } 
20. g4!? -- ( { Black still has to work for it, as } 20...Qxh2 21.Qxf7 Kb8 22.Bd3 { , as well as @@StartFEN@@2kr4/1p3pQp/p1bp4/8/2B3P1/8/PPPq3P/1K3R2 b - g3 0 20@@EndFEN@@ 20...Be4 21.Qc3! Qxc3 22.bxc3 are both not fully drawn just yet. Of course, if Black analyzes even further, I assume it is possible to work it out into some 3 vs 2 rook endgame or something, but for that, we have the much fresh 11. Rg1!? option. } )
