1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 e6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 a6 
5. c4 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { The Sicilian Kan is not a bad opening, but when played with aggressive intentions, it probably is. Back in the day, it was a way to get the opponents out of the book early and try to steer the game to a complicated middlegame leaving all the pieces on the board. However, as } 5.c4!? { line emerged, Black started facing a big dilemma. Are they going to fight for a draw with no winning chances, or are they ready to take the risk and go for a very dangerous version of the passive hedgehog structure? } ) ( { This line has become very popular, particularly after Carlsen used it to beat Anand in the World Championship [/variation/26063177] match in 2014. Back in the day, Black was usually permitted to get a Sicilian-type play after } 5.Nc3 { or } ) ( 5.Bd3 { , but the } ) ( 5.c4 { trend has discouraged many players who used Kan as a fighting weapon. } ) Nf6 ( { Black can also start with } 5...Qc7 { ( } 6.Nc3 Nf6 { transpose), but there is no point in delaying 5... Nf6. } ) 
6. Nc3 d6 ( { Here is a big moment for Black. The preferred choice of the engines, } 6...Bb4 { leads to very one-sided positions where Black tries to grind out a draw, while } ) ( 6...Qc7 { going for a hedgehog is really not liked by modern engines. Besides the hedgehog being a very passive setup in general, there are new trends with White going for more aggressive setups than the short castle. } ) ( { This is very primitive. Usually Black at least plays } 6...Qc7 { and only after } 7.a3 { goes for a hedgehog. } ) 
7. Bd3 ( { The setup with } 7.Be2 { is also very effective, then Be3, O-O and f4-Bf3. However, to remain consistent, I will recommend the Bd3 setup here, intending f4, just like in 6... Qc7 7. a3 b6 system. } ) Be7 
8. O-O O-O { The setups with Nc6 are famously not very much fun for Black in the hedgehog. We can play Be3 and Black will find it difficult to develop the c8 bishop actively and get any meaningful counterplay. } 
9. f4 b6 
10. Be3 Bb7 
11. Qf3 Nbd7 
12. Qh3 { As usual, a beautiful and instructive sample line is incoming. } Rc8 
13. Rad1 { Before launching the attack, in most cases, it is a big mistake to forget to include the a1 rook into the game. In fact a very common mistake among many less experienced players. } Re8 
14. Bc2! {[%cal Ge4e5]} { The c4 pawn is not really hanging now, due to the threat of e5, and stepping out of Nc5 is nice preparation before launching the g-pawn forward. } Qc7 
15. g4! { Now is the moment. } g6 
16. Nf3!? {[%cal Gf4f5,Gf3g5]} ( { I like the incoming line, but the standard } 16.g5 Nh5 17.f5 { which is what most strong players would do is also very strong. } ) Bf8 ( { The best attempt to hold on. If } 16...Qxc4 { then f5 followed by Bb3 is crushing. } ) 
17. Ng5 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gf4f5]} { The knight is ready to sacrifice itself. } h6 
18. Nxf7! {[%csl Rg8]} { Everything is facing the kingside and it's not wonder the sacrifice is sound. } Kxf7 
19. g5 { The computer attacks masterfully. } Nh7 
20. e5 {[%cal Gc2g6]} { Introducing Bxg6+! ideas. } h5 
21. Rd2! {[%cal Gc2g6,Gf4f5,Ye5d6,Yf1d1,Yf8d6]} { Apparently, this preparatory move is a good idea. Black anyway can't do anything against the threat of Bxg6+ and now exd6 is a threat as well, since we can double with Rfd1 next. } Rcd8 { Preparing for exd6. } 
22. Bd4! {[%cal Gc2g6]} { The threat of Bxg6 is now deadly. Black's position is collapsing. } *

