5. c4 ( { The Sicilian Kan is not a bad opening, but when played with aggressive intentions, it probably is. Back in the day, it was a way to get the opponents out of the book early and try to steer the game to a complicated middlegame leaving all the pieces on the board. However, as } 5.c4!? { line emerged, Black started facing a big dilemma. Are they going to fight for a draw with no winning chances, or are they ready to take the risk and go for a very dangerous version of the passive hedgehog structure? } ) ( { This line has become very popular, particularly after Carlsen used it to beat Anand in the World Championship [/variation/26063177] match in 2014. Back in the day, Black was usually permitted to get a Sicilian-type play after } 5.Nc3 { or } ) ( 5.Bd3 { , but the } ) ( 5.c4 { trend has discouraged many players who used Kan as a fighting weapon. } ) Nf6 ( { Black can also start with } 5...Qc7 { ( } 6.Nc3 Nf6 { transpose), but there is no point in delaying 5... Nf6. } ) 
6. Nc3 Qc7 ( { Here is a big moment for Black. The preferred choice of the engines, } 6...Bb4 { leads to very one-sided positions where Black tries to grind out a draw, while } ) ( 6...Qc7 { going for a hedgehog is really not liked by modern engines. Besides the hedgehog being a very passive setup in general, there are new trends with White going for more aggressive setups than the short castle. } ) ( { The most popular move, not surprisingly, since the Kan players are too desperate to get their hedgehog and don't want to start defending with } 6...Bb4 7.Qd3 d5 { . } ) 
7. a3 { We take the time to prevent Bb4. } b6 { The most respected move order here. Now White has a few different setups. } 
8. f4!? {[%cal Gf1d3]} { I propose the most ambitious setup with f4 and Bd3. The standard plan with Be3 f3 is also very viable of course, but this feels even more testing. } Bb7 { The computer recommends delaying d6. } 
9. Bd3 Nc6 ( { The top choice of the engine, played by Neiksans [/variation/25670077], who is a bit of an expert in Kan, I heard. For } 9...d6 { , see 8... d6, we play } 10.f5 { there. } ) 
10. Nxc6 Qxc6 
11. Qe2 Bc5 
12. Be3 Bxe3 
13. Qxe3 O-O ( { Neiksans went for a funky line. Instead } 13...Qc5 { going for a slightly worse endgame, might be safer. } ) 
14. O-O-O { Brave play by Tari against Neiksans. } b5 { Black is in desperate need for play, so the pawn sac is called for. } 
15. cxb5 axb5 
16. Bxb5 Qc7 
17. Kb1 Rfb8 
18. Rd3! ( { So far Tari played well, but now he goes astray with the natural } 18.a4?! { . } ) Qa5 ( { Preparing for } 18...Bxe4 { in a more subtle way. } ) { Best. } 
19. Rd4 {[%mdl 32768]} { Black doesn't have enough for a pawn here. } Bc6 { Good attempt at counterplay. } 
20. Ra4! { Black can't afford to simplify, being a pawn down. } Qxb5 { Sacrificing the queen is Black's best shot. } 
21. Nxb5 Rxa4 
22. Nd6 Nxe4 
23. Rd1 Nxd6 
24. Rxd6 { Converting will take a while, especially against the best defense, but it doesn't look like Black should have full compensation for the queen and the engine also confirms that. } *

