1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 e6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nc6 
5. Nc3 Qc7 
6. Be3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { The Taimanov is a major opening that has been around for ages and remains popular across all levels. Top players too, keep returning to it, in search of an unclear, double-edged play. It was my main weapon for Black on and off since my childhood and all the way until 2015. I have to say, that the impact of newer engines on this opening might have been the greatest.

When I started playing it against top players the mainline was the English Attack with } 6.Be3 a6 7.Qd2 { , followed by long castle and f3. As Black started discovering new trends there, involving Be7 instead of the traditional Bb4 and also an occasional early capture on d4, White started also expanding with various f4 ideas, on move 8, 9 and sometimes even as early as move 6.

Then suddenly @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppqp1ppp/2n1p3/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Be3 a6 7.Qf3 showed up on the radar around the year 2014, as the engines started appreciating this unusual queen development. That line continued to trouble Black players for many years and eventually, I came up with some shady Ne5 h5 setup. Sooner or later, though, as the engines got stronger and I noticed more and more issues in that setup, I abandoned it and with it the entire Taimanov. Black eventually found some antidotes, but they never seemed too appealing.

Around 2020-2021, as the Taimanov started making its comeback to the top level, White also discovered that there is more to it than just 6. Be3/Qf3. Suddenly @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppqp1ppp/2n1p3/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Be3 a6 7.g4!? became trendy and a few other trends appeared, causing more headaches for the Taimanov fans. That said, my original Taimanov issue of @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/ppqp1ppp/2n1p3/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Be3 a6 7.Qf3 never left and now, on the White side of it, this is the variation I want to recommend. } ) Nf6 
7. Qf3 ( { This doesn't actually avoid } 7.Qf3 { , it only allows an extra option of } ) ( 7.f4!? { . } ) Bb4 ( { The easiest to recommend, since most players anyway go for } 7...a6 { , transposing to 6... a6. } ) { This is not good here. } 
8. Ndb5! { Pointing out that a6 is played for a reason. } Qb8 ( { If } 8...Qa5 { then just } 9.O-O-O { with Nd6+ after a6. } ) 
9. a3 { Kicking the bishop back and going for the endgame is the most direct approach. } Be7 
10. Qg3 Qxg3 
11. hxg3 O-O { Now the computer proposes a funky sequence. } 
12. f4!? {[%cal Ge4e5]} ( { Introducing the idea of e5 and also getting out of } 12.O-O-O Ng4! { . } ) d6 
13. O-O-O { Gaining a tempo on the d6-pawn. } Rd8 
14. Be2 a6 
15. Nd4 {[%cal Gg3g4]} ( { White is better here, with g4 to follow and some sort of an initiative even in the endgame. Even more epic is } 15.Nc7!? Rb8 16.g4! { when it is surprisingly hard to trap our knight on c7, while we get some tempi to setup a kingside attack. } ) *

