7. Qf3 ( { This is the recommended setup. The trendy } 7.g4 { is explored in other courses and no longer holds the same surprise value. The good (not so) old } ) ( 7.Qf3 { is still as legit as ever. Black now has many options, but everywhere we have our ideas. } ) Ne5 { This, followed by h5 was my system back in 2015 period and even though it has always been dubious, the modern engines really push it to the edge. } 
8. Qg3 h5 { I am proud to see people still playing it now, but I no longer feel responsible for it... } 
9. h4 { The computer really likes it. The main debates back in the day were centered around 9. O-O-O or 9. f4 which often would transpose. The point back then was that the engine was pushing White players in the wrong direction, where I was able, thanks to deeper analysis get a good position with Black. However, this is no longer the case, since nowadays the engines no longer flip their evaluations upon reaching larger depths. After 9. h4 there are some transpositions. } Nf6 ( { The most common move. } 9...d6 { should transpose to either 9... b5 line [/variation/25079575] or 9... Nf6 after 10. O-O-O. } { 9.O-O-O now see 9... b5 or 9... Nf6 depending on which move Black plays. For the passive 9...Bd7 , I once again recommend the plan with 10.Bg5! followed by Rhe1, Kb1, a3 and eventual f4!. } ) 
10. O-O-O {[%mdl 32768]} d6 ( { Black is at a crossroads here. } 10...b5 { , which allows a dangerous sacrifice or a timid } ) ( 10...d6 { . Both have been played equally frequently so far. } ) { Black is trying to finish the development without allowing any sacrifices. } 
