1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 e6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nc6 
5. Nc3 a6 ( { This version of Taimanov has some advantages and disadvantages compared to } 5...Qc7 { . Against the } ) ( 5...Qc7 { move order, we go for } 6.Be3 a6 7.Qf3 { setup, with Qg3 being one of its main ideas. Here, the queen is not yet on c7, so Qf3 setups are less poisonous. At the same time, now Nxc6 capture becomes much more attractive, since the move a6 is at best useless and possibly even somewhat harmful for Black, weakening the b6-square and creating a pawn weakness. } ) 
6. Nxc6 {[%mdl 32768]} { Definitely the most principled move! } bxc6 ( { Capturing to the center is how Black plays. The endgame after } 6...dxc6 { is obviously terrible, after we trade queens, develop the bishop to f4 and castle long, enjoying Black's dark square weaknesses. } ) 
7. Bd3 ( { There is a massive new trend with } 7.Qd3 { , intending Qg3, but the recent top games suggest that the line is not so simple for White. Instead, I will recommend the old line, which is also easier to understand. We develop in a more standard way. } ) Qc7 { An attempt to switch around the move order, but we are a bit of move order experts ourselves. } 
8. Qe2!? Bb7 ( { Very nasty, intending to meet } 8...Nf6 { with } 9.e5! { . } ) ( { There are some games with the dubious } 8...Bd6 { . The way to go there is to go for O-O-O plan, with, for example, } 9.Bd2 { , when the attack on the h2-pawn is pointless. } ) 
9. O-O d5 
10. Bg5 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ga1e1]} { The most active move and the top choice of the engine as well. } Nf6 { Black finally starts developing the kingside. } 
11. f4 Be7 
12. Rae1 { We bring all our pieces towards the kingside. } h6 
13. Bh4 O-O 
14. e5 { Closing the position is the way to go. } Ne8 
15. Bxe7 Qxe7 
16. Nd1 {[%cal Gd1e3,Gf4f5,Gb2b3,Gc6c5]} { In this closed pawn structure, the knight should leave c3. In this particular case, it is heading towards e3, supporting the f5 push. } c5 
17. b3 { Addressing the threat of c4. } g6 
18. Ne3 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gf4f5]} ( { Also interesting is } 18.Nf2!? { with the idea that } 18...h5 { can now be met with } 19.Nh3!? { . However, this happened in a 2021 corr. game that White won - Duchardt-Almarza [/variation/25628832]. Our plan is quite simple, we want to go for the g4-f5 pawn push on the kingside. } ) *

