7. Qg4!? ( { The old main line of } 7.Bd2 { is also very good, but Black can then get a reasonably robust position with } 7...Nxc3 8.bxc3 Bf8 { , so I prefer the more direct approach. } ) Kf8 { The best try and the way Jobava played this system, the last strong player to still experiment with the pin variation. } 
8. Bd3! {[%mdl 32768]} h5 ( { This seems to be the strongest. Apparently } 8...Nxc3 { is not a threat because of } 9.Nxe6+! { and Qxb4+ resource. } ) { Trying to give the h8 rook some air. } 
9. Qe4 Kg8 {[%cal Rd4e6]} { Threatening Nxc3, as the king has just got out of the Nxc3 Nxe6+! tactic. } 
10. Ndb5 { The simple Bd2 is also possible, but this is strong. } a6 
11. O-O!? Nc6 ( { No need to move anything. } 11...axb5 { is now met with } 12.Nxd5 exd5 13.Qxb4 { . } ) ( { The engine also suggests } 11...Qf8 { , after which we can sacrifice the pawn with } 12.Nd4 { or } { 12.Nd6 , with overwhelming positional compensation for the pawn, in both cases, thanks to a better king and much better development. } ) 
12. Nd6 {[%csl Rc8,Rg8,Rh8]} { The c8-bishop is the issue. } Nxc3 
13. bxc3 Bxc3 
14. Bf4! { Sacrificing the exchange for complete dominance over the dark squares. } Bxa1 
15. Rxa1 b5 {[%csl Rc8,Gd6,Rg8]} { We have a picturesque domination, but now comes the moment to start creating threats. } 
16. h4! {[%cal Gf4g5,Ga1e1,Ge1e3,Ge3g3]} { Gaining some time for Bg5 action. } Qxh4 
17. Qe3! {[%cal Gf4g5,Ga1d1][%csl Ra8,Rc8,Rg8,Rh4]} { For the h-pawn, we gained further time. Black isn't going to survive this, as there is no adequate defense against eventual Bg5. Don't forget to also include the a1 rook into the game, with Rd1 next, so that Black doesn't have Qd4 after Bg5. } *

