1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 e5?! { This is an incredibly ugly opening. Black gets a terrible position here, if White knows just a little bit of theory. } 
6. Bb5+! {[%mdl 32768]} { This check is essential, but it's quite obvious. This is why the Najdorf exists and Black plays 5... a6 first, before going for e5. } Bd7 { Trading the light-squared bishops is even worse for Black. } 
7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 
8. Nde2 ( { It is important not to go for } 8.Nf5 Nxe4 9.Nxg7 { complications and keep it simple. The knight is heading to g3, from where it overprotects e4 and eventually, it will reroute itself towards d5 via f1-e3. } ) Qc6 
9. Ng3 Nbd7 
10. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6]} { We are always happy to trade a defender of the d5-square. } g6 
11. Qd3 { There are many alternatives on this and the coming moves, but I really like how incredibly straightforward the game Korneev-Alvarez [/variation/25165909] went in 2012. } h6 
12. Bxf6 Nxf6 
13. Nf1 {[%cal Gf1e3,Ge3d5]} Be7 
14. Ne3 O-O 
15. Ncd5 {[%csl Gd5]} { And White hasn't won the game, but definitely won our hearts. If I could play this position every day, I would stop making Chessable courses and play this position every day. Black is completely helpless in the most classic case of bad bishop vs good knight. } *

