[ECO "B56"]

1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 e5?! { This is an incredibly ugly opening. Black gets a terrible position here, if White knows just a little bit of theory. } 
6. Bb5+! { This check is essential, but it's quite obvious. This is why the Najdorf exists and Black plays 5... a6 first, before going for e5. } Nbd7 { The attempt to keep some intrigue, but with precise play White still gets domination over the weak d5-square. } 
7. Nf5 {[%mdl 32768]} { The most obvious and the best. } a6 
8. Ba4!? ( { I believe this to be much more unpleasant than the most common } 8.Bxd7 { capture. } ) b5 
9. Bb3 Nc5 
10. Bg5 {[%csl Gd5]} { It is clear the remainder of control over the d5-square is getting away from Black completely. } Bxf5 
11. exf5 Be7 
12. Bxf6 { Trading the last defender of the d5-square. } Bxf6 
13. Qf3 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4]} { One of the many moves that attempt to neutralize Black's counterplay attempts and solidify the control of the light squares and currently the top choice of the engines. } e4 ( { Only chance, since } 13...O-O 14.O-O-O { followed by Ne4 and Bd5 leaves Black with no counterplay at all. } ) 
14. Nxe4 Bxb2 
15. Rd1 Nxe4 
16. O-O! {[%cal Gd1d6,Gf3a8][%csl Re4]} { Black can't move the knight because of Rxd6! trick. } O-O 
17. Qxe4 {[%csl Gb3,Gf5]} { White has a much better bishop and the doubled f-pawns are great, since the one on f2 covers the king, while the one on f5 is going to help the potential pawn storm. White has a clear risk-free advantage and the drawish tendency of the opposite-colored bishops should not be exaggerated since there are a lot of heavy pieces on the board still. } *

