[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's 1. e4  -  Part 3"]
[White "19) Black's Sidelines Without ...e6"]
[Black "2...d6 with 4...Nf6 5.Nc3 Bd7 #1"]
[Date "2023.03.29"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/25026779"]
[ECO "B56"]

1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 d6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 
5. Nc3 Bd7 { This sort-of Najdorf, is not so terrible but is clearly too artificial. Black is trying to keep the flexibility and play something in between the Najdorf 5... a6 and the Classical Sicilian 5... Nc6. I considered going for the 6.h3 setup, staying in our comfort zone, as the positions would be similar to the Najdorf lines I cover, but finally, I decided to go for the most principled move 6. f3! where Black seems to be forced into playing a bad line of the Najdorf English Attack. } 
6. f3 {[%mdl 32768]} e5 ( { This is how Black plays. Some go for } 6...Nc6 { followed by g6, but that would be a dubious version of the Dragon, as we follow with the Yugoslav Attack setup, with Be3 Qd2 and O-O-O. } ) 
7. Nb3 Be7 
8. Be3 O-O 
9. Qd2 a5 { This is the system they play here. The idea is to play this extremely dubious a5 variation of the Najdorf and hope that the opponent is not familiar with the English Attack. True, since we play 6. h3 against the Najdorf, we aren't, but we will cover this particular line, so basically we will be. } 
10. a4 {[%csl Gb5]} { We have to stop the advance of the a-pawn and claim the weak b5-square. } Na6 { Black usually sends the knight to b4, via a6 or c6, Na6 being the more flexible of the two, since it also keeps the option of Nc7. } 
11. O-O-O { In this position Black is staring at their own light squared holes on b5 and d5 and the only way to make this work somehow is to try and prepare a d5 or a b5 break, which would turn things around completely. However, with accurate play by White, it seems that the desired breaks aren't quite possible. } Nc7 {[%cal Gd8b8,Gb7b5,Ge3b6][%csl Gb6]} { Trying to get Qb8 and b5 is noble, but we will block this idea with Bb6. } 
12. Bb6 Qb8 
13. Kb1 Bc6 
14. Bd3 { Preparing to meet Nd7 with takes and Nd5. } Nd7 
15. Bxc7 Qxc7 
16. Nd5 Bxd5 ( { If } 16...Qd8 17.Bb5! { Black's d6 pawn will fall. } ) 
17. exd5 {[%cal Gd3b5,Gd2e2][%csl Gb1,Gb5]} { In such a position, when White is able to control the b5 square, there is not much Black can do, in terms of counterplay. We eventually will try to break through on the kingside or the center. } *

