11. O-O-O { In this position Black is staring at their own light squared holes on b5 and d5 and the only way to make this work somehow is to try and prepare a d5 or a b5 break, which would turn things around completely. However, with accurate play by White, it seems that the desired breaks aren't quite possible. } Nb4 ( { The most often played move, but this line is just not good for Black. } 11...Be6 { will transpose to 11... Nb4 move order. } 12.g4 Nb4 { see 11... Nb4. } ) 
12. g4 {[%mdl 32768]} Be6 { This is a huge transposition into a5 line of the English Attack. Believe it or not, at some point I played this as Black as well, but back then the engines were really really weak and I had one cheapo I was hoping to get in the mainline which had me excited. To be very honest, it was a fault of a friend of mine, who just talked me into this. As the engines got stronger, the right move order for White was discovered and Black was left without any counterplay, in a strategically dubious position. } 
13. Kb1 Rc8 
14. g5! ( { This is an old tabia. Now the epic line for Black went } 14.h4? d5!! 15.g5 Ne8 16.exd5 Bf5 { , followed by Nd6 and sometimes even b5!. Black's pieces unleashed their full potential and life was beautiful. Unfortunately for Black, though, it was soon discovered that White can start with 14. g5! and none of this works. } ) { It is important to not allow any d5 shenanigans and start by clarifying where the f6-knight is heading. } Nh5 ( 14...Ne8 { Now it's important for White to keep up the pace and not allow d5! break. } 15.f4! { Black's dreams of getting in d5 are crushed. } ) 
15. Bb5 f5 
