1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 a6 
3. c4 ( { The O'Kelly Sicilian is a little bit back at the higher level, because turned out it is not too bad a system. It is also played a lot at the lower levels because the standard } 3.d4 { is not really good, as after } 3...cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5! { White doesn't have the Ndb5 response and Black jumps out with Bb4 next. All that said, if White knows what they are doing, then Black will not have any fun. } ) { One of the few good responses. We are aiming for a Maroczy bind setup. } Nc6 ( { For other options, like } 3...e6 { or } ) ( 3...d6 { I propose to take a look at the Sicilian Kan [/course/159903/15] chapter, where I cover the standard hedgehog positions. The O'Kelly [/variation/25026783] connoisseurs go for the concrete play with } ) ( 3...Nc6 { . } ) 
4. d4 cxd4 
5. Nxd4 { Here both Nf6 and e5 first lead to the same thing. } Nf6 ( 5...e5 6.Nf5 d5! { The point. } 7.cxd5 Bxf5 8.exf5 Nd4 9.Nc3 Nf6 { see 5... Nf6. } ) ( { And } 5...e6 6.Nc3 Nf6 7.a3 Qc7 { transposes to the Kan chapter. [/variation/25045765/#/7/b] } ) 
6. Nc3 e5 
7. Nf5 { The principled way to go. } d5! ( { The point of this entire system. } 7...d6?! { is also quite frequent, especially in amateur games, but leads to an extremely comfortable edge for White after something like } 8.Ne3 Be6 9.Ned5 ) 
8. cxd5 Bxf5 
9. exf5 Nd4 
10. Bd3 { The best option. White returns the d5-pawn, but keeps the bishop pair. } Be7! ( { Black should start with Be7 and O-O, since } 10...Nxd5? { which is, by the way, played a lot, is bad because of } 11.O-O Be7 12.Be4! { . } ) 
11. O-O O-O 
12. Re1 Nxd5 
13. Nxd5 Qxd5 { This is the tabia that both sides are aiming for. Black is quite solid, but White got a clearcut opening advantage with no risk. } 
14. Be4 ( { It's also possible to start with } 14.Qg4 { . } ) Qd7 { The natural retreat. } 
15. Be3 Rad8 { This is recommended by Sielecki in his course, but it still looks slightly better to me, as we can take on d4 at some point and get a pleasant opposite-colored bishops position with attacking prospects. } 
16. Bxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Starting with a useful move like } 16.g3 { is also possible. } ) exd4 { A queen trade trade will lose Black the b7-pawn in a bad version. } 
17. Bd3 { We have good long-term attacking prospects, despite that Black has a solid position. Our f5-pawn is cramping Black's kingside, while our own king's shelter is intact. } *

