1. e4 c5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 Qb6 { This is actually a very common system, when Black attempts to 'play for a win' or 'take us out of book'. Well, here is your book. } 
5. Nb3 Nf6 ( 5...e6 { will likely just transpose to 5... Nf6. } 6.Bd3 { We invite Black to transpose into the 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. Bd3 line [/variation/25026793]. } 6...Nf6 { Almost everyone has played this, transposing into 5... Nf6 variation. If Black delays this with a move like Qc7 or a6, we can consider going for a c4 Maroczy-type structure as well. } ) 
6. Nc3 e6 
7. Bd3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { I had looked at various options here and decided that this is the simplest setup to recommend. The old mainline with } 7.Qe2 { is no longer deemed as the most challenging by modern engines. Alternatively, there are some Be3/a3 setups, but I prefer to get the bishop out to d3 first and try to do without the move a3. } ) Bb4 { This setup doesn't seem very appealing here, when we can just castle short. } 
8. O-O Bxc3 { Doubling our pawns is not too worrying, with Black missing the dark-squared bishop with all the weak dark squares. } 
9. bxc3 O-O 
10. Ba3 { There are plenty of good options. } Rd8 
11. Nd4 {[%csl Gd6,Ge5]} { We try to keep some sort of a grip on the dark squares, by tactical means. } d6 
12. Nxc6 Qxc6 ( { If } 12...bxc6 { we also go } 13.e5! dxe5 { and now } 14.Be7! { -xf6 with trouble coming up on the kingside for Black. } ) 
13. e5! Ne8 ( { With a cheap tactic in mind - } 13...dxe5 14.Bxh7+ { . } ) 
14. Re1 { Black is extremely passive and is yet to develop the c8 bishop. We have got the bishop pair and a very active position. } *

